To create a digital card (like a simple personal webpage or portfolio) that you can host on GitHub and generate a QR code to share it, follow these steps:

✅ STEP 1: Create Your Digital Card (HTML)

Here’s a clean and modern HTML digital card template:

html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
  <title>Pranay Bhise - Digital Card</title>
  <style>
    body {
      font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif;
      margin: 0;
      padding: 0;
      background: #f5f5f5;
      display: flex;

      height: 100vh;
    }

      background: #ffffff;
      padding: 30px;
      border-radius: 16px;

      width: 90%;
      max-width: 400px;
    }

      margin: 10px 0;
      font-size: 24px;
    }

    .card p {
      margin: 5px 0;
      font-size: 16px;
      color: #555;
    }

    .card a {
      text-decoration: none;
      color: #007bff;
    }
  </style>
</head>

    <p>Sales Executive</p>
    <p>📞 9201838993 / 8982462135</p>
    <p>✉️ <a href="mailto:Pranay.rsfp@gmail.com">Pranay.rsfp@gmail.com</a></p>
    <p>🔗 <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/pranay-bhise-6aa6b8327" target="_blank">LinkedIn Profile</a></p>
  </div>
</body>
</html>

✅ STEP 2: Host It on GitHub

  1. Create a GitHub Account (if you don't have one)

  2. Go to https://github.com/new

  3. Create a new repository named yourusername.github.io

    (Replace yourusername with your GitHub username)

  4. Upload the HTML file (name it index.html)

  5. Commit the changes

  6. GitHub will automatically publish it at:
    https://yourusername.github.io

✅ STEP 3: Generate a QR Code

  1. Visit https://www.qr-code-generator.com/

  2. Paste your GitHub Page URL (e.g., https://yourusername.github.io)

  3. Download the QR code and use it in print or digital media.

Perfect! Here's a step-by-step guide to host your digital card on GitHub Pages and then generate a QR code for it:

✅ STEP 1: Create a GitHub Repository

  1. Go to https://github.com/ and log in.

  2. Click the “+” icon (top right) → New repository

  3. Repository name:
    ➤ Use this format if you want a direct domain:
    yourusername.github.io
    (Replace yourusername with your GitHub username)

  4. Make it public

  5. Click "Create repository"

✅ STEP 2: Upload Your HTML and Logo

  1. On your new repo page, click “Add file” → “Upload files”

  2. Upload:

    • Your HTML file (e.g., pranay_digital_card.html)

    • The logo image (RSFP LOGO.jpeg)

  3. Click Commit changes

✅ STEP 3: Rename Your HTML File (Optional but recommended)

If your file is not named index.html, rename it:

  1. Go to the file in the repo

  2. Click the pencil ✏️ icon to edit

  3. Change the filename to index.html

  4. Scroll down and Commit changes

✅ STEP 4: Enable GitHub Pages

  1. Go to Settings of the repo

  2. Scroll to Pages section (in the left sidebar or under "Code and automation")

  3. Under Source, select Deploy from a branch

  4. Select:

    • Branch: main (or master)

    • Folder: / (root)

  5. Click Save

  6. After a few seconds, you’ll see a URL like:
    https://yourusername.github.io/

✅ STEP 5: Generate a QR Code

  1. Go to: https://www.qr-code-generator.com/

  2. Paste your GitHub Pages URL (e.g., https://yourusername.github.io/)

  3. Click Download

  4. Use the QR anywhere (print, email, social, etc.)

✅ Optional: Want It Branded?

Let me know if you want:

  • A custom domain (like pranay.rsfp.in)

  • Custom QR design (colors, logo in center)

  • Mobile optimization

I can help with those too!

You said:
how to add the other business card in same username but the links are differnt
ChatGPT said:

Great question! You can absolutely host multiple business cards (or any webpages) under the same GitHub username, as long as:

  • Each card is in its own separate repository, OR

  • All are in one repo, but each card is inside its own folder, and you link to them using subpaths

✅ OPTION 1: One Repo Per Card (Most Simple)

You already have:

arduino
https://rsfp110.github.io/ECARD-/

To add a second card:

🔧 Steps:

  1. Go to https://github.com/new

  2. Create a new repo — e.g., ECARD-PRANAY

  3. Upload the second HTML file and image/logo

  4. In repo settings → enable GitHub Pages:

    • Source: Deploy from a branch

    • Branch: main

    • Folder: / (root)

  5. GitHub will publish it as:

    arduino
    https://rsfp110.github.io/ECARD-PRANAY/

Repeat for each card.

✅ OPTION 2: One Repo, Multiple Folders (Advanced)

You can have one main repo like ECARD and place each card in a subfolder:

pgsql
ECARD/
│
├── index.html              ← Main card
├── pranay/
│   └── index.html          ← Pranay's card
├── varun/
│   └── index.html          ← Varun's card

Then they will be available at:

  • https://rsfp110.github.io/ECARD/ (default)

  • https://rsfp110.github.io/ECARD/pranay/

  • https://rsfp110.github.io/ECARD/varun/

🔁 But for this to work, you need to build a static site structure or use GitHub Actions or Jekyll, which is more technical.

🧾 Summary – Which Should You Use?

MethodURL StyleRecommended For
One repo per cardhttps://rsfp110.github.io/ECARD-2/Easy setup
One repo with foldershttps://rsfp110.github.io/ECARD/name/Centralized control

Let me know which way you prefer, and I can guide you step-by-step (or even generate the folder structure for you)!
